      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Other Debate: Campaign Spending</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Nick Nyhart (Public Campaign), commenting on Oct 3 Op-Ed article by Sen John F Kerry and William F Weld on limiting campaign spending, says self-policing is not the same thing as comprehensive campaign reform</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While Senator John F. Kerry and William F. Weld, the former governor of Massachusetts, are to be commended for their effort to limit spending in their 1996 Senate race against each other (''Money Needn't Win,'' Op-Ed, Oct. 3), self-policing is not the same thing as comprehensive campaign reform.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While Senator John F. Kerry and William F. Weld, the former governor of Massachusetts, are to be commended for their effort to limit spending in their 1996 Senate race against each other (''Money Needn't Win,'' Op-Ed, Oct. 3), self-policing is not the same thing as comprehensive campaign reform.</p>
        <p>Mr. Kerry's and Mr. Weld's model didn't stop special interests from currying favor with contributions, nor did it help open up the electoral system to people without wealthy supporters or personal fortunes. What's needed is a comprehensive approach that provides candidates with an alternative source of clean, public financing for their campaigns.</p>
        <p>As a co-sponsor of Senator Paul Wellstone's Clean Money, Clean Elections Act, Mr. Kerry has stepped forward as a national leader seeking a real solution. Let's hope others follow that example.</p>
        <p>NICK NYHART  Exec. Dir., Public Campaign  Washington, Oct. 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
